<DOC><DOCNO> AP890112-0235 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-01-12-89 0607EST</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights TwoTakes   01-12 0522</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, Two Takes,0544</SECOND><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. and former Sen.Howard Baker have scrapped negotiations about a possible managementrole for him at the troubled Wall Street giant, which recentlyagreed to a record $650 million plea bargain on securities fraudcharges.   By mutual consent, Drexel and Baker said Wednesday, ``The talksended, and the senator will not be taking a position with theinvestment baking firm.''   Steven Anreder, a Drexel spokesman, would not elaborate beyondthe statement, and there was no answer at the Tennessee office ofBaker's spokesman Thomas Griscom late Wednesday.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The rapid rise in oil prices since OPEC agreed toslash production six weeks ago has exceeded most people'sexpections, but energy analysts aren't ready to declare the cartel'saccord a success.   Prices of Middle East oil remain well below OPEC's target of $18a barrel, and some recent gains may be lost if the excess oilproduced by the cartel late last year ever hits the market, analystssaid Wednesday.   Since Nov. 28, when the Organization of Petroleum ExportingCountries announced it would curtail production, Middle Easterncrude oil has risen more than $3 a barrel _ from approximately $11to about $15.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Federal aviation officials ordered inspectionsof 300 Boeing 737s for possible cross-wiring of engine warningsystems, which is one possibility being investigated as contributingto the British Midland crash.   The Federal Aviation Administration order on Wednesday came afterthe British Civil Aviation Authority ordered similar checks, alongwith stepped-up inspections of engines on three types of aircraftusing the same engines as the British Midland Airways Boeing 737-400that crashed Sunday, killing 44 people.   The ``air worthiness directive'' issued by FAA AdministratorAllan McArtor did not cover engine inspections and would not groundany U.S. aircraft.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Only one U.S. worker in 100 was tested for druguse last year, the government said in new study that sharply reducedprevious estimates of how many employers conduct such tests.   The Labor Department survey, conducted last summer and releasedWednesday, found that only 3 percent of all employers employingabout 20 percent of American workers had drug-testing programs.</TEXT><DATELINE>PROSPECT HEIGHTS, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Household International Inc. plansto dissolve its $1 billion manufacturing empire, narrowing thecompany's operations to financial services after four years ofrestructuring.   The company said Wednesday it would spin off three of itsmanufacturing units to its shareholders, creating three independentcompanies, and sell the other six, which include Thermos Co.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Warner Communications Inc. has closed itslong-delayed, $1.2 billion merger with Lorimar Telepictures Corp. ina deal that solidifies its position as the leader in entertainmentprogramming.   The two entertainment concerns had agreed to a merger last May,but the completion of the deal on Wednesday was delayed because oflegal complications arising from Lorimar's ownership of severaltelevision stations, which it sold.   The merger includes a swap of stock valued at about $635 millionand Warner's assumption of about $600 million in Lorimar debt.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>